               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17650918-71-person780">
                  Mary 
                  Wilkinson 
               <interp inst="t17650918-71-person780" type="surname" value="Wilkinson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17650918-71-person780" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17650918-71-person780" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My husband took the prisoner home in order to take him apprentice: he went with us before the Alderman: I did not in the least imagine he was guilty of any thing; he went to be a witness; there he confess'd, that Davis told Barrow, if they did not get him to do something as bad as they, he would blow them; that they made him drunk, and then he took silver and halfpence out of the till.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17650918-71-person781">
                  Joseph 
                  Barrow 
               <interp inst="t17650918-71-person781" type="surname" value="Barrow"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17650918-71-person781" type="given" value="Joseph"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17650918-71-person781" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the prisoner take 5 s. 6 d. out of the till on the 1st of August; and on the Wednesday following he took 3 s. 6 d. more.</p>
               <p>Q. Had you us'd to give him liquor?</p>
               <p>Barrow. No; we have drank a little liquor together: he saw Davis come down into the cellar to take liquor away, and Davis told me he would give him some liquor, that he should not tell.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I did not take any money.</p>
               <p>
